SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 721
By Yarbro
A RESOLUTION to honor and congratulate Jessica McClintock of
Lipscomb Academy on winning the TSSAA
Division II girls' individual bowling state
championship.
WHEREAS, we take great pleasure in recognizing those dedicated student athletes who
serve as the heart and soul of their schools and communities while displaying the fortitude of a
champion; and
WHEREAS, one such outstanding individual is Jessica McClintock of Lipscomb
Academy, who recently won the TSSAA Division II girls' individual bowling state championship;
and
WHEREAS, recording 1,081 pins and a 180.2 average in the semi-final round, Ms.
McClintock bested forty-seven bowlers to finish first and advance to the championship match;
and
WHEREAS, in the final match, Ms. McClintock felled 176 pins to defeat her opponent by
37 pins and claim the state championship; and
WHEREAS, she was also a valuable member of the Lipscomb girls' bowling squad that
won the state team title and brought home the gold; and
WHEREAS, Jessica McClintock epitomizes all that is good in today's student athlete, as
she has achieved a premier level of success in competition while exhibiting the highest degree
of character in all aspects of life; and
WHEREAS, the perseverance, determination, work ethic, and talent of this young
woman not only made possible a championship season but also surely bode well for her future
success; and
SJR0721
013027
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Ms. McClintock has distinguished herself as a dominant bowler of whom we
can all be proud, and she is most worthy of our approbation at this time; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor and congratulate Jessica McClintock of
Lipscomb Academy on winning the TSSAA Division II girls' individual bowling state
championship and wish her all the best in her future endeavors.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
